        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Henry Cohen Esqre. Parnass&#44; Messrs Ab. Hart. M. Gans<lb/>
                <del>Messrs H. Cohen&#44; Parnass. A. Hart&#44; M. Gans</del><lb/>
                L. Hans &#38; A. Frechin&#44; Adjunta of R R M I.<lb/></p>
            <p>Gentlemen<lb/></p>
            <p>Last fall on hearing of your <del>&#63;</del> Regarding&#93; deliberation about the renting<lb/> of seats in our synagogue&#44; I was prompted to ask for a reduction of <del>my</del><lb/> salary.  Our Secretary acknowledged immediately the receipt of my<lb/> note&#44; and stated&#44; in behalf of the Cong&#44; that no offer I made would be accepted&#44;<lb/> if there arose occasion for it.  Subsequently&#44; our Parnass&#44; in the course of<lb/> a friendly conversation&#44; expressed the opinion&#8212;founded on sanguine hopes&#8212;that<lb/> the proposed relinquishment would not become a necessity.  A few weeks<lb/> after I received a communication&#44; emanating from your body&#44; with the<lb/> information that you <del>thought it needful to</del> had acted on my offer and lessened<lb/> my emolument of five hundred dollars a year.  For obvious reasons I <del>desired</del> requested<lb/> the concurrence of the Cong&#44; and our Parnass&#8212;of his own accord&#8212;kindly<lb/> <del>called</del> paid a call for a special meeting to that effect.  But neither that&#44; nor the <del>regular</del><lb/> <del>one</del> semiannual one provided for by the constitution secured a quorum.  Not wishing&#44;<lb/> of course dishonorably to take &#91;crossed&#45;out&#93; advantage of the absence of action on<lb/> the part of the Cong&#44; and&#44; <del>on the other hand</del> at the same time&#44; feeling uncertain<lb/> of what that action might be&#44; I abstained twice form applying for<lb/> the requisite orders.  The present secretary of Our Sabai&#44; however paid me two<lb/> quarters&#44; reserving in cash&#44; at my request&#44; hundred and twenty<lb/> five dollars&#44; subject to the <del>determination</del> decision of my constituents.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>But now that gentleman urges me to procure said orders&#44; so <del>as to</del> that he may<lb/> &#91;crossed&#45;out&#93; arrange ten books of the Cong.  In asking for them&#44; I beg<lb/> to add&#58; that sincerely anxious as I am to guard the synagogue at any<lb/> sacrifice <del>of my own</del> demanded at my hands&#8212;against danger&#44; family obligations&#8212;also sacred&#8212;claim<lb/> <del>demand</del> my serious consideration.  To perform those duties to their full extent<lb/> during the last six months&#44; despite the reduction&#44; has been a strain<lb/> <del>and a labor</del> which I had not anticipated&#44; and which I would like to<lb/> <del>have</del> avoid hereafter&#8212;unless <del>essential for</del> imperative on me to <del>undergo them with a view</del> bear it for<lb/> <del>to</del> the continuance of our synagogue&#39;s honorable standing.<lb/></p>
            <p>I <del>do not deny</del> admit that I could so limit my expenses as to make even <del>much</del><lb/> less than what I have lately received suffice&#44; but it would pain me to be com&#45;<lb/>&#45;pelled to stifle the sentiments of the heart&#59; to <del>subject</del> deprive my children<lb/> <del>to privations to which they have not been used</del> of comforts they have hitherto enjoyed&#44; and principally to deny<lb/> them the hope of not being left entirely destitute in case of my<lb/> death.<lb/></p>
            <p>Nevertheless&#44; if you deem it <del>proper</del> essential that the two back orders<lb/> and the next be drawn in accordance with your past action&#44; <del>and</del> reserving the final <del>with a reservation for the future action</del><lb/> <del>of</del> decision for the congregational meeting previous to Rosh Hashan&#225;&#44; I will submit<lb/> to <del>your deliberation</del> the determination of your body.<lb/></p>
            <p>Very respectfully<lb/>
                S Morais<lb/>
                June 1879<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
